{"author":{"id":"b78c39e7b13f90a5827abfba043255fe7a4ede1499df23f110fffe5abfa44adc"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1771519253,"nonce":"tHFr3+np1GzSaooKQ0Q8Z76l1rM=","metadata":{"github-id":"I_kwDOQ241x87sRI8z","github-url":"https://github.com/rolker/ros2_agent_workspace/issues/235","origin":"github"},"title":"Periodic workspace health sweep","message":"## Problem\n\nIssue #234 covers **opportunistic** quality improvement — agents audit packages as they happen to work on them. This companion issue covers the other half: **periodic, workspace-wide health checks** that catch drift, inconsistencies, and rot that accumulate between active development sessions.\n\nThese checks run on-demand (e.g., `make health` or as part of `status_report.sh`) rather than being triggered by working on a specific package.\n\n## Two Domains\n\nThe workspace has two distinct audit scopes with different concerns:\n\n### Workspace Infrastructure (the \"shop floor\")\n\nThe agentic tooling, scripts, and instructions that agents rely on to do their work. If these are wrong or stale, agents waste time or make incorrect assumptions.\n\n| Check | Description |\n|-------|-------------|\n| **Instruction consistency** | CLAUDE.md, project-level `.agents/README.md` files, and any other agent instruction surfaces don't contradict each other (e.g., one says \"use `ament_target_dependencies`\" while another says \"use modern CMake targets\") |\n| **Script relevance** | Scripts in `.agent/scripts/` are still referenced by CLAUDE.md or Makefile targets — no orphaned scripts, no references to scripts that don't exist |\n| **Template freshness** | Templates in `.agent/templates/` match current conventions (e.g., if we changed the AI signature format, templates should reflect that) |\n| **Knowledge file accuracy** | Files in `.agent/knowledge/` don't reference deprecated tools, removed scripts, or outdated patterns |\n| **Repo config drift** | `.repos` files match what's actually checked out in `layers/main/` — catches repos that were added/removed without updating the config |\n\n### Hosted Projects (the \"products\")\n\nThe ROS 2 packages that actually run on the robot. Correctness matters more here — a stale doc is annoying, a missing dependency crashes the build.\n\n| Check | Description |\n|-------|-------------|\n| **Dependency alignment** | Python `import` statements and C++ `#include` directives are declared in the corresponding `package.xml`. Flag missing `\u003cdepend\u003e`, `\u003cexec_depend\u003e`, or `\u003cbuild_depend\u003e` entries. *(Note: Python import-to-ROS-package mapping is imperfect — this should flag candidates for human review, not auto-fix.)* |\n| **Launch file validation** | Every `Node(package=..., executable=...)` in `*.launch.py` files references a package and entry point that actually exists in `setup.py` / `CMakeLists.txt` |\n| **Architecture doc freshness** | If a project has architecture documentation (e.g., node/topic diagrams), flag nodes or topics that exist in code but not in docs, or vice versa |\n| **Stale build artifacts** | Directories in `build/` or `install/` for packages that no longer exist in `src/` — these cause \"ghost node\" confusion |\n| **Dead entry points** | Executables defined in `setup.py` `console_scripts` or CMake `install(TARGETS)` that are never referenced by any launch file |\n\n## Relationship to Existing Tools\n\n- **`status_report.sh`** already covers worktree hygiene and branch status — this issue explicitly does NOT duplicate that\n- **`validate_workspace.py`** already checks repo config — this extends that concept to broader consistency\n- **Issue #234** covers the quality checklist and \"audit on entry\" rule — this issue provides the complementary periodic sweep\n\n## Implementation Approach\n\nA single entry point (script or Makefile target) that runs all checks and produces a consolidated report. Could be:\n- A Python script (`.agent/scripts/workspace_health.py`) that handles both domains\n- Or separate scripts per domain wired together via a Makefile target\n\nOutput should be a readable Markdown-formatted report with severity levels:\n- **ERROR**: Will break builds or cause incorrect behavior (missing dependencies, broken launch references)\n- **WARNING**: Quality gap or drift that should be addressed (stale docs, orphaned scripts)\n- **INFO**: Minor housekeeping opportunities (unused entry points, old build artifacts)\n\n### Non-goals\n\n- Auto-fixing code or metadata — the sweep identifies problems, humans/agents decide how to fix them\n- Replacing CI — this catches things CI can't (cross-package consistency, doc drift, infrastructure staleness)\n- Duplicating `status_report.sh` — no worktree/branch/PR status\n\n## References\n\n- #234 — Incremental package quality improvement (opportunistic, per-package)\n- Inspired by discussion with Gemini on workspace maintenance patterns\n\n---\n**Authored-By**: `Claude Code Agent`\n**Model**: `Claude Opus 4.6`","files":null}]}